<b>"Wtf you mean shadowknights can snare?"</b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ucendan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cendan</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 503<br> <font color=#E9D756>(2/4/02 12:21:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=269.topic&index=118>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cendan</span><hr size=1> Tuan,<br>
<br>
If they act on it they are free to accept forgiveness as anyone would.  Once again this goes into the discussion on living in sin vs falling into sin.<br>
<br>
Someone who walks by a store and decides to shoplift has fallen into sin.  Someone who leaves their wallet at home and goes to the store expecting to come home with groceries, as they do every Thursday, is living in sin.  The first can be forgiven, the second must repent (change of heart) before forgiveness is granted.<br>
<br>
Your example doesn't invoke sympathy from me because they don't have to act on it.  Certainly I was attracted to women before I was married and if I had acted on my attraction then it would have been sin.<br>
<br>
God's plan was to create a diverse people rather than clones or robots.  He did so.  <br>
<br>
I am curious here, and this is not meant as an insult or as baiting... just a simple question.  I have an opinion and to prove I am not baiting to come back with something I am going to give you my opinion with the question, so here goes.<br>
<br>
Is it okay for a brother and a sister to sleep together, and even get married (barring local legal interference).  Condition is this... they have no plans to reproduce, even use more than one method of birth control (don't want 2 headed babies after all).<br>
<br>
Now here is my opinion, which is obvious but I want to express my opinion/curiousity of how it relates to homosexuality.  Now, both are detestable to God.  They are not part of His plan.  However, to someone who says "is it wrong to love?" is there a difference?  I don't see how there could be.  I know society accepts one more than the other but the argument could be made that both have been practiced through history, and they have. <p><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" height="1">
