</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/utuan00dorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tuan00Dorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1052<br> <font color=#E9D756>(2/4/02 2:02:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=269.topic&index=119>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cendan</span><hr size=1> Cendan, before I answer that question...<br>
<br>
&quot;Your example doesn't invoke sympathy from me because they don't have to act on it. Certainly I was attracted to women before I was married and if I had acted on my attraction then it would have been sin.&quot;<br>
<br>
Straight people<br>
1) It is sinful to steal<br>
1) It is sinful to act before marriage<br>
2) It is not sinful to act after marriage<br>
<br>
Gay People<br>
1) It is sinful to steal<br>
2) It is sinful for gay people to act at any time (on the same sex)<br>
<br>
See, here is the problem I have Cendan.  You are saying it is not sinful for straight people to act on their instinctive feelings that God gave them about love (attracted to the opposite sex), but it is sinful for gay-people ot act on their instinctive feelings that God gave them about love (attracted to the same sex).<br>
<br>
Your example of stealing is not the same, because it is wrong for -everyone- to act on something like stealing.<br>
<br>
Since you do not believe in anything such as evolution, the only way someone would be born with the ability to love someone else in a sexual manner is for God to give that to them. Right?<br>
<br>
So lets say there are 4 people.  1 straight woman, 1 straight man, 2 gay women.<br>
<br>
The two gay women love each other.  They do not, cannot and do not want to love the man in the same way beacuse of how God made them.<br>
<br>
The straight man and straight women love each other because of how God made them.<br>
<br>
All 4 of these people want to act on their love because it is how God made them.<br>
<br>
According to you, it is sinful for the two gay women to act on this love in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> any circumstance</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, yet it is not-sinful for the man and women to act on this love given they are married.<br>
<br>
It looks like God has made different rules here.  The people he made gay, they are condemned to hell if they act on their love which God bestowed upon them.  Yet he also made people straight, and they are allowed to act on this love after marriage.<br>
<br>
--conclusions below, for ease of reading---<br>
<br>
Cendan, doesn't that sound extremely hyprocritical of God?  According to what you said, God is setting different rules for people here <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> because</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> he has created them differently in the first place.<br>
<br>
To set the same rules on love for people that were made to love completly different wouldn't make any sense would it?<br>
<br>
Why should 1 person be able to act on the love that they were born with, through God, but someone else it is wrong?<br>
<br>
========================<br>
<br>
About the brother and sister.<br>
<br>
An interesting argument.<br>
<br>
We should first define the type of love we are talking about.  People seem to be born with the ability to love (in general) and the ability to love someone in a different, sexual way.<br>
<br>
You love your family and friends in one way, you love your mate in another.<br>
<br>
It makes sense to say, someone was born to love men sexually or someone was born to love women sexually.  But it is not the logical equivilent to say, someone was born to love a family member sexually.<br>
<br>
After saying that, I still don't know how much of an answer I have.  If a brother and sister <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> truely</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> loved each other in the same sexual way we are describing with a mate, and without a doubt felt the same way about the family member as others experience with other people; then I guess I would have to say it is ok.<br>
<br>
The question remains if it is possible for someone to be born like that.  Maybe people are actually born with a gene determining if they love men or women, and part of this gene also includes their blood line, which makes it so they cannot  be born to love a family member in that sexual way.<br>
<br>
Maybe this gene was mutated to allow for gayness.. and also could have mutated in such a way that their bloodline is not an issue when dealing with their sexuality?<br>
<br>
Who knows, I think the genetic argument could be a good one.  It is possible that this brother and sister truely do love each other in a sexual way.  Their parents passed on some defective gene that allowed for them both the ability to sexualy love a family member.<br>
<br>
Sounds a little out there I know, but it is in the same respect fairly likely.<br>
<br>
All in all, I would say <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> most</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of the &quot;brother-sister&quot; things are infatuation with someone whom you expirmented with sexually at a young age... They conditioned themselves into thinking it was real love, and may not even know the difference between different types of love.<br>
<br>
The difference between gay love and this is, I am willing to bet that almost every single brother-sister marriage or &quot;love&quot; has come out of sexually experiementing with them at a young age causing a fake infatuation.<br>
<br>
When you look at gay people, most of them are not conditioning themselves at a young age by having gay sex and claiming this is the way they are (although I do believe this is a possible reason in some cases why someone thinks they are gay).  Most of them just feel this way, it's the way they are and they have felt it their whole life and never been comfortable with trying to love someone of the opposite sex that way.<br>
<br>
So overall, I think it's very different saying &quot;is it wrong to love?&quot; in these cases, because brother-sister is caused by infatuation when you don't understand feelings yet.  Gay people usually don't discover until later in their life that this is how they are.<br>
<br>
damn that got long.... <p>Tuan {Cupcakes} the Vicar</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulithahntalon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lith Ahntalon</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 200<br> <font color=#E9D756>(2/4/02 6:56:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=269.topic&index=120>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cendan</span><hr size=1> Yup, I think the little quote went right over Cendan's head. Face it guys, he is going to see only what he wants to see and ignore or simply be unable to see the rest. <p><img src=http://eshamlin.home.mindspring.com/lith.jpg></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulukariatrueheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lukaria Trueheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 110<br> <font color=#E9D756>(2/4/02 11:44:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=269.topic&index=121>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Tealdare1</span><hr size=1> Tuan:<br>
