<br>
<br>
<br>
You got it. If asking where I get this though, mostly from John. Specifically, here are a few times its mentioned : 1John 2:7, 1John 3:11, 1John 3:23. 1John 4:7, 2John 1:5, 2John 1:6, John 13:34, John 15:12, John 15:17.<br>
<br>
To get it in detail though, Read Rom 13:8 - here it specifically mentions that the other commandments are summed up into loving your neighbor as yourself. Christ gave the commandment (as cited above) to love one another. Thereby = 2 commandments.<br>
<br>
I don't even know if it was you who mentioned the commandments or not, but really, my point was that if you are a Christian and you are living legalistically, then you are limiting your new identity in Christ. Having a law-focus instead of a Christ-focus doesn't lead you into greater understanding and spritual growth, instead it keeps you tallying a &quot;score&quot; of sorts to see where you measure in relation to God's perfection. /shrug. We're not perfect, we're not going to be so therefore, don't focus on that - instead focus on Christ and begin trying to grow more into Him. Seriously, a really great book that describes a lot of what I mean here is called &quot;Walking in Victory&quot; by Dennis McCallum.<br>
<br>
Your other points about what is needed are a given. I would add that are all encompassed when you accept Christ. You are repentant, you state your belief, and you also are baptized by the faith. <br>
<br>
Immersion into water actually is not required in the New Testament - Its Jesus' blood that washes away our sins - however, if you don't believe that - its ok. Lets not argue that point as its not really central here - thats a tangent. <br>
<br>
I don't agree with you on the losing salvation thing. I don't believe salvation can be lost. Again, this is not something that I feel is important enough to argue in this forum. I don't see what the point was though for Jesus to die, if we can lose our salvation... we could still sacrifice animals instead. <br>
<br>
Really, the main difference between us is living under grace, I think. I believe that once Christ is in your heart, that you are now living under Grace. Again refer to that &quot;Walking in Victory&quot; for more information on that.<br>
<br>
As for your statement <br>
Quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
 <br>
<br>
Sick of reading about people who invited Jesus into their heart. You know... Jesus invited you into his Church, into His family. The terms are His. You can invite Him into your heart all you want... but He doesn't accept your invitation you accept His. When you die for the world and raise on the third day then you can make your own church and handle invitation policy.<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
