</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/bemarr.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=rittdabard>rittdabard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 85<br> <font color=#E9D756>(2/5/02 6:25:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=269.topic&index=130>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Expectations and consequences of God</span><hr size=1> I have one hypothetical question just so I can see where people stand...<br>
<br>
Six people die...<br>
<br>
Person A lived an exemplerary life and any sin he committed was of the most trivial kind. (he still feals guilty about drinking too much on New Years three years ago, even though he didn't get stupid drunk) He died sacrificing himself so that another may live. He lived life closer to the scriptures as close as anyone since Christ, even as Ned Flanders said, &quot;Obeying the rules that contradicted other rules&quot; He was a Catholic, and went by all their doctrine. He leaves his heirs penniless but with nothing but good memories of him.<br>
<br>
Person B Lived a comfortable life. He did as he preacher told him. Missed church once a year to prepare for their traditional Super Bowl party, but he figures God can forgive him for some family time. He has been fully acknowledged as a member of the local Baptist Church. He always thought about doing some work with the homeless but figures the time he lost from work would be too costly so he donates money instead. <br>
<br>
Person C Was born filthy rich. Spent his youth trying to blow his enormous fortune. Fell into several vices. Eventually realized his life was missing something. Originally started going to church to regain the respect he lost living it up. Falls in love with a preachers daughter. He does as she wishes and becomes a full fledged member of her fathers Lutheran Church.<br>
They marry. Occasionally he thinks about his wild youth fondly, but he is quite content in the role he has grown into as a family man. As he is dieing he realizes he never did enough good and begs forgiveness.<br>
<br>
Person D Was a strong leader of morals in his community. He is responsible for the largest decline in violence in his communities known history. He never marries dedicating his life to the welfare of others. He encourages the youth to stay close to their families and has helped lengthen the lives of the elderly and has a gift for helping women through childbirth. He is the High Preist in a tribe of Animists(worshippers of animal spirits) and has never even heard of Jesus or Satan.<br>
<br>
Person E Is a devout Christian. He belongs to a smaller breakaway sect. He believes that he is on the right path and truly has understanding of God. He knows that redemption is not as easy a path as many make it out to be and knows merely providing sanctity for his own soul is selfish and Jesus will see that. He works at a bookstore that sells religious paraphenelia. During the weekends he burns abortion clinics and picketts the funerals of AIDS victims. He has helped reduce the population of homosexuals in the community by posting pictures taken of local residence who go to the adult bookstore and the boy bar in the next town. His greatest accomplishment however, is that because of a program where he posted the addresses of abortion doctors and there families and there phone numbers on the internet he has made abortion clinics almost defunct in his state. <br>
<br>
Person F is an atheist. He lost his virginity after he was married. He doesn't drink, or do drugs. He is active in community service and has a firm set of morals, but does not believe it is his right to impose them on others. He allows his wife to practice her religion, but refuses to take part in it. This bothers her but she loves him, and that cannot change. In fact she doesn't realize how lucky they are in that that is the only real source of turmoil in their relationship. He encourages his children to go to church with their mother. He tells them when they are adults religion is a choice they will have to make, but assures them that their belief is pleasing to him.<br>
<br>
1 Do you belive A will make it to Heaven or Hell? Why?<br>
2 B?<br>
3 C?<br>
4 D?<br>
5 E?<br>
6 F?<br>
<br>
I know ther are many elements that make these things hard but few are actually made up they are conglomerations of real life people I have read about/known. It is all hypothetical and I just want to see how people think about God.<br>
<br>
Ritt<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/utuan00dorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tuan00Dorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1063<br> <font color=#E9D756>(2/5/02 6:38:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=269.topic&index=131>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Expectations and consequences of God</span><hr size=1> There are no rules for this so called heaven and hell.<br>
<br>
I don't even know why this heaven people believe in can be so wonderful.  Lets say that I die, right now and went to heaven.  It's supposed to be a better place, right? So I am taken away from my family and friends, everyone I care about.  But then someone says &quot;You will be happier in heaven&quot;..  Really? So all the love I had on earth was just a delusion, heaven is where it's really at?  I will suddenly just &quot;be happy&quot; in heaven with God, all the people I cared about mean nothing?<br>
<br>
So what about all the people that care about me... My mom, she is supposed to be comforted beacuse I am &quot;in a better place&quot; and know that I am &quot;happier&quot; without her?<br>
<br>
I don't think so.  To believe that we will be happier in heaven is to deny us the love we are capable of now, it teaches us our life now is not real.<br>
<br>
I can't stand the thought of being anywhere else. <p>Tuan {Cupcakes} the Vicar</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulurikeen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lurikeen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 281<br> <font color=#E9D756>(2/5/02 8:33:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=269.topic&index=132>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Expectations and consequences of God</span><hr size=1> Rittdabard, you have proposed a set of circumstances that pronounce a dillemma for the Christian &quot;moralist&quot;. The Christian moralist will say that all others will be judged by Christ (not by humans) and according to &quot;his word&quot;. Unless salvation formula x is followed, Christ will condemn the individual to an eternities torment. You see it is because of God's good grace that a person is saved and not by works alone, they preach. So, the Christian moralist pronounces what the &quot;word of Christ&quot; is, what &quot;grace&quot; means, condemns to hell, and then blames God by declaring that &quot;God alone judges through his word&quot;.<br>
<br>
The problem is that the Christian moralist is always faced with the issue that his view of God's &quot;grace&quot; and &quot;salvation&quot; may be incorrect. That indeed, he is breaking the rule not to judge or condemn &quot;lest ye be judged&quot; by another who is greater. On one hand he beats the drum of his interpretation hoping it is correct, on the other he walks the path of legalism smugly condemning all others to the pit.<br>
<br>
<br>
Kanibaal :<br>
<br>
